  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "To help stop a sunburn from peeling, you can take the following steps:\n\n1. **Moisturize Regularly**: Apply a gentle moisturizer or aloe vera gel frequently to keep your skin hydrated. Look for products that are fragrance-free and designed for sensitive skin.\n\n2. **Stay Hydrated**: Drink plenty of water to help your skin heal from the inside out. Hydration is crucial in the healing process.\n\n3. **Avoid Sun Exposure**: Stay out of the sun until your sunburn heals completely. If you need to go outside, wear protective clothing and use a broad-spectrum sunscreen with a high SPF.\n\n4. **Cool Compresses**: Apply cool, damp cloths to the burned areas to soothe the skin and reduce inflammation. This can help minimize itching and discomfort.\n\n5. **Gentle Cleansing**: When showering, use lukewarm water instead of hot water, and opt for a mild, hydrating body wash. Pat your skin dry instead of rubbing it with a towel.\n\n6. **Avoid Scratching and Peeling**: Resist the urge to pick or peel at the sunburned skin, as this can lead to infection and scarring. Let the skin naturally shed as it heals.\n\n7. **Topical Treatments**: Over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream can reduce inflammation and itching. However, it should be used sparingly and not on large areas of the body without consulting a healthcare professional.\n\n8. **Vitamin E and Other Oils**: Some people find that vitamin E oil or other nourishing oils can help soothe and moisturize sunburned skin.\n\nIf your sunburn is severe, blisters form, or you experience significant pain, it may be wise to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation and treatment.",
